   Professional biographical information:

   Ph.D. Plant Physiology Texas A&M University 1991

   B.S. Biology Cornell University 1983

   A.S. Math/Science C.C. Finger Lakes (N.Y.) 1981

   Positions held

   Microbiologist/ Support Scientist, USDA-ARS, Appalachian Fruit Research
   Station, 1996 to present.

   Plant Physiologist/ Post-Doctoral Research Associate, USDA-ARS,
   Appalachian Fruit Research Station, Dr. Michael Wisniewski,1994 to
   1996.

   Post-Doctoral Research Associate, Cornell University, Department of
   Soil, Crop, and Atmospheric Sciences, Dr. Tim Setter, 1992 to 1994.

   Selected Publications:

   Callahan, A., Dunn, L., Fishel, D., Knott, M., Artlip, T., and
   Wisniewski, M. (1998) Stress and Fruit Ripening. FOCUS 19 (supplement):
   12-13.

   Bassett,C.L., Artlip, T.S., Nickerson, M.L., Wilson, C.L., and Hixson,
   C.V. (1998) Cloning of a 26S proteasome subunit 7 homologue from peach
   (GenBank Accession No. AF041258). Plant Physiol.117:332.

   Artlip, T.S. and Wisniewski, M.E. (1997) Tissue-specific expression of
   a dehydrin gene in one-year-old Rio Oso Gem peach trees. J. Amer. Soc.
   Hort. Sci. 122: 784-787.

   Artlip, T.S., Callahan, A.S., Bassett, C.L., and Wisniewski, M.E.
   (1997) Seasonal expression of a dehydrin gene in sibling deciduous and
   evergreen genotypes of peach (Prunus persica [L.] Batsch). Plant Mol.
   Biol. 33: 61-70.

   Wisniewski, M., Close, T.J., Artlip, T.S., and Arora, R. (1996)
   Seasonal patterns of dehydrins and 70-kDa heat-shock proteins in bark
